Retention Index Normal Adjustment

Degnan, David J. & Bramer, Lisa M. & Flores, Javier E.

Last updated: 09/23/2022

1 Adjusting Normal Distribution Assumptions

Here, we investigate the effect of adjusting each metabolite’s retention index score to their retention index distribution \(\bar{x}\) and \(s\). This approach was conducted with the ri_score_holdout_analysis script. Results per metabolite can be visualized in Trelli1, where the distribution of rank changes (new rank subtracted from original rank) is plotted. Points are colored by sample type and ordered on the x-axis from smallest to largest new rank. Points indicate the median of the distribution, while lines indicate the range for both true positives and true negatives.

1.1 Results Summary

Figure 1: Average proportion of true positives (n = 87) and true negatives (n = 78) at ranks 1, 2, and 5.

We see definite improvement with this approach for true positives at ranks 1, 2, and 5 with 4, 2.5, and 2-fold changes, respectively. We do not see any improvement for true negatives at rank 1, but we do see improvements at ranks 2 and 5 (Fig. 1). This plot only shows general trends overall, following the adjustment of the retention index score to each metabolite’s estimated retention index mean and standard deviation. The trelliscope display (Trelli1) shows the trends per metabolite. Below, we have a single example of these trends.

1.2 Single Example

Figure 2: An example from the trelliscope display of the true positive rank change distribution following our normal distribution adjustment. The point is the median rank change, and the line shows the range of rank changes.

In L-Alanine D7, we see improvements in the rankings of the true positives for most of the samples, as a decrease in rank is desirable (Fig. 2). Sample type may have an effect on a per metabolite basis, as the trelliscope shows that fungal and soil samples often perform worse than CSF, Plasma, and Urine samples with this adjustment, though the trends vary widely per metabolite.

Figure 3: An example from the trelliscope display of the true positive rank change distribution following our normal distribution adjustment. The point is the median rank change, and the line shows the range of rank changes.

In L-Alanine D7, we see improvements in more than half of the rankings of the true negatives, as an increase in rank is desirable (Fig. 3). Most true negatives are from standard samples, with some cases of fungi and soil crust. There are no true negatives for the other sample types in this subset of selected true negatives, where each true negative must have a corresponding true positive in their bin.

1.3 Rank Change

Figure 4: True positive retention index difference (query minus reference) standard deviations plotted against absolute means and separate by skews less than or greater than 1. Points are colored by rank change improvements at rank 1, where better >= 0.05, worse is <= -0.05, and the rest are labeled no change.

There is no obvious trend between improvement at rank 1 and query retention index statistics (mean, standard deviation, and skew) (Fig. 4). This means that our three summary statistics alone do not fully describe what makes a good rank change. That said, adjusting the score with higher means and standard deviations generally results in no change or better scores.

Figure 5: Counts of changes at rank 1 using this adjustment, where better >= 0.05, worse is <= -0.05, and the rest are labeled no change.

With this approach, 55% of our 87 metabolite subset have better rankings, 36% experience no change, and 9% have worse rankings (Fig. 5). Next, we will try using the normal distribution probabilities instead of the kernel as the RI score. See the next markdown for more details.
